What types of holsters do you make? Inside the waistband (IWB) concealed carry is our specialty but we can make outside the waistband (OWB) as well. We have designed custom mag carriers for 3 Gun competitions to include mag holsters for a Kriss Vector.

One of the screws came loose and I lost it, can you replace it? Yes, we offer lifetime warranties on the holsters and will mail you a replacement to keep you going. We only ask that in certain cases, you pay for shipping costs if required.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Iver Johnson 'Safety Automatic' Revolver in .22
location: Southern Overland Park, KS 66062, Kansas City, Kansas
postcontent:
I have for sale an antique Iver Johnson 'Safety Automatic' revolver, second model, in an unusual .22lr.

7 shot, double action revolver.

Here's one that sold for $185 + shipping on Gunbroker. I haven't found any other working examples that have sold.
http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=476804656

Many of these guns were made in .32 and .38, but .22 is rare since not many were made in this caliber.
This is a second model, made from 1898-1908 (roughly), so it's even more uncommon than the third model that was made from 1908-1941

Overall it's in decent condition, some flaking on the left side mostly, a bit of rust on the top strap and the bore has some pitting. Both grips are broken on the bottoms, one is built up with some putty but it doesn't effect function. Both seem to hold to the frame well enough.
It's a small little thing, only 6 1/2 inches full length.
But it seems to be perfectly serviceable, the lockup is tight and opening/closing is smooth. Double action trigger is heavy but that's just the nature of it.

I haven't shot it but it seems to dent primers OK. Would make for a neat little range toy. Don't shoot hypersonic or hot loads in it though, I would stick to subsonics or even powderless loads to keep it in shape.

Cash or trade.

title: For Sale:  Austrian Mauser 98 in 7.62x51 NATO
postcontent:
With bills creeping up on me, I've got to part ways with my old Mauser in 7.62 NATO. The action is smooth as glass, and the craftsmanship is amazing. Even though the stock has seen better days. The original wood finish was removed because it was unpleasant to look at, and its currently bare wood, ready for a possible refinishing project, or if you prefer, it could easily be sporterized. The receiver is "in the white", meaning it never had any bluing, and it could be polished to a mirror-like shine if desired. 

The side of the receiver reads "WAFFENFABRIK, STEYR, AUSTRIA"

I've only shot about 40 rounds from it. It functions great and the bore looks clean and shiny. The rifling is very visible. 

This rifle was a 7mm Mauser that was re-barreled with a 1903 Springfield barrel back in the 1960's in Austria for a contract with Chile. The chamber was shortened to accommodate the standard 7.62x51 NATO round. This is only intended to fire 7.62 NATO, not full-powered .308 loads. Commercial .308 like PMC bronze or with a muzzle velocity under 2800fps should be fine. I've fired TulAmmo .308 out of this without problems. Accuracy was decent with the cheap ammo too.

I have 10 or so stripper clips for this rifle I can throw in for free. They are Swedish mauser clips and they work better than any clip I've ever tried.

I'm also including 20 rounds of Silver Bear .308 ammo for free.

I'm asking $200 for the rifle with the stripper clips. I will meet you near a gun shop where you can freely check the weapon over before you buy.

NO SHIPPING, AND BUYER MUST BE WILLING TO MEET WITHIN 15 MILES OF KETTERING, OHIO.
